Remove a Subfolder (e.g., test2) and Update Git
1Ô∏è‚É£ Navigate to your repo
cd ~/automation-lab

2Ô∏è‚É£ Delete just that subfolder

Run:

rm -r python/test2


‚úÖ This removes only the folder test2 and its contents.
Your python folder stays untouched.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Check what changed
git status


You should see:

deleted:    python/test2/test2.py
deleted:    python/test2/

4Ô∏è‚É£ Stage the deletion
git add -u


or simply:

git add python/test2

5Ô∏è‚É£ Commit your change
git commit -m "Removed folder test2"

6Ô∏è‚É£ Push to GitHub
git push


‚úÖ Now the test2 folder is gone both locally and on GitHub.

üß† Quick Summary
cd ~/automation-lab
rm -r python/test2
git add -u
git commit -m "Removed folder test2"
git push




========================================================
# Script to remove folder in git

#!/bin/bash
# ======================================================
# removeproj.sh ‚Äì Safely remove a Python project folder
# Usage: ./removeproj.sh  (you will be prompted for the folder name)
# ======================================================

# Ask for project name if not given
if [ -z "$1" ]; then
  read -p "Enter the project folder name to remove (inside python/): " PROJECT
else
  PROJECT=$1
fi

BASE_DIR=~/automation-lab
PROJECT_DIR=$BASE_DIR/python/$PROJECT

# Check if the folder exists
if [ ! -d "$PROJECT_DIR" ]; then
  echo "‚ùå Folder '$PROJECT_DIR' does not exist."
  exit 1
fi

# Confirm deletion
read -p "‚ö†Ô∏è  Are you sure you want to delete '$PROJECT_DIR'? (y/n): " CONFIRM
if [[ ! "$CONFIRM" =~ ^[Yy]$ ]]; then
  echo "‚ùé Deletion cancelled."
  exit 0
fi

# Remove the folder
rm -rf "$PROJECT_DIR"
echo "üóëÔ∏è  Removed folder: $PROJECT_DIR"

# Commit and push the change to Git
cd $BASE_DIR
git add -u
git commit -m "Removed project folder: $PROJECT"
git push

echo "‚úÖ Folder '$PROJECT' removed and change pushed to GitHub."


